04266nam a22004815i 9780228000440DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280004407 a10.1515/97802280004402doi  a(DE-B1597)656253  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aSB123.57b.S36 2019 7aBUS0720002bisacsh04a631.52330962231 aSchnurr, Matthew A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfrica's Gene Revolution :bGenetically Modified Crops and the Future of African Agriculture /cMatthew A. Schnurr. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource :b4 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tA Political Ecology of Africa's Gene Revolution -- tThe Promotion, Science, and Regulation of GM Crops -- tTalking Technology: Plant Breeding for Agricultural Development -- tRules and Regulations: Governing GM Crops in Africa -- tGMO 1.0: First-Generation GM Crops Targeting Insect Resistance and Herbicide Tolerance in Commodity Crops -- tGM Cotton in South Africa, Burkina Faso, Sudan, and Uganda -- tGM Maize in South Africa and Egypt -- tGMO 2.0: Second-Generation GM Crops Targeting Traits and Crops That Matter to Poor Farmers -- tTwo Crucial Precedents: Virus-Resistant Sweet Potato and Insect-Resistant Maize in Kenya -- tWater Efficient Maize for Africa in Kenya -- tGM Banana in Uganda -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs development donors invest hundreds of millions of dollars into improved crops designed to alleviate poverty and hunger, Africa has emerged as the final frontier in the global debate over agricultural biotechnology. The first data-driven assessment of the ecological, social, and political factors that shape our understanding of genetic modification, Africa's Gene Revolution surveys twenty years of efforts to use genomics-based breeding to enhance yields and livelihoods for African farmers. Matthew Schnurr considers the full range of biotechnologies currently in commercial use and those in development - including hybrids, marker-assisted breeding, tissue culture, and genetic engineering. Drawing on interviews with biotechnology experts alongside research conducted with more than two hundred farmers across eastern, western, and southern Africa, Schnurr reveals a profound incongruity between the optimistic rhetoric that accompanies genetic modification technology and the realities of the smallholder farmers who are its intended beneficiaries. Through the lens of political ecology, this book demonstrates that the current emphasis on improved seeds discounts the geographic, social, ecological, and economic contexts in which the producers of these crops operate. Bringing the voices of farmers to the foreground of this polarizing debate, Africa's Gene Revolution contends that meaningful change will come from a reconfiguration not only of the plant's genome, but of the entire agricultural system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculturezAfrica. 0aCropsxGenetic engineeringzAfrica. 0aTransgenic plantszAfrica. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228000440?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228000440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228000440/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles